Change has been successfully rebased and submitted as 7c4c52cb4e855b1f25f25e87d3b7f9cafa63e157

This patch is ready to be reviewed.  However, I should note that the changes for this patch use the same approach I do in in a previous patch https://gerrit.openbmc.org/c/openbmc/bmcweb/+/58928/comments/fbde0a61_babbe6e3.  

Any concerns in that patch will likely be applicable here as well.  I will update this patch accordingly if that happens.
const_iterator
Done
const_iterator
Done
My comments are nitpicky.  Up to you if you want to fix them.

Nit, I think at this level of the code, the routes have already been checked that they start with /redfish/v1, and this code is redundant.  Also, if we're incrementing through the URI anyway on line 510, if we wanted to do the checks, should we just do them there and only iterate once?

We do already check for the leading /redfish/v1 in beginAggregation() so it's fine to remove it here.

> Also, if we're incrementing through the URI anyway on line 510, if we wanted to do the checks, should we just do them there and only iterate once?

We could try, but the code would look really ugly.  The URIs in the topCollections array do not begin with "/redfish/v1" so we really don't want to include them as part of currentUrl which is getting built one segment at a time.
nit, this const is redundant if you're using const_iterator.

So I ran some tests and surprisingly, const_iterators can be modified.  I changed "it" on the previous line to const_iterator and it built without complaints.  I did the same for "it" in addPrefixToItem() and the tests associated with that function passed.
Right, you can change a const iterator, but you can't change the value contained within it.  In general, we don't declare variables const that we believe won't be modified.  NBD.
